<s docid="FBIS4-26242" num="5" wdcount="3"> 19 Jun 1994</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26769" num="17" wdcount="31"> Floods hit Guangdong, Guangxi, 
Hunan, Jiangxi, Fujiang and Zhejiang provinces following the first 
heavy rains and floods which typically hit China from the south to the 
north from June to August.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26242" num="16" wdcount="29"> By four o'clock this afternoon 
the level recorded at the Changsha monitoring station had risen to 
38.93 m, some 0.56 m higher than the highest figure ever previously 
recorded.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26242" num="26" wdcount="17"> So far, more than 500,000 
soldiers and local residents have moved in to help fight the 
floods.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26245" num="5" wdcount="3"> 20 Jun 1994</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26245" num="17" wdcount="23"> Flood water has entered urban 
and suburban areas of Wuzhou city, and most of its transport and 
telecommunications with the outside were suspended.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26245" num="19" wdcount="25"> The speed of the flood-water 
was recorded as 46,200 cu [cubic] m per second, the most ferocious 
since the founding of New China in 1949.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26614" num="24" wdcount="27"> [Governor] This year, Hunan has 
been hit by a flood of a severity unseen for the past 100 years in 
terms of both water level and quantity.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26516" num="5" wdcount="3"> 22 Jun 1994</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26516" num="17" wdcount="21"> Among nine cities and 
prefectures in Fujian, those seriously hit by the flood are Sanming, 
Nanping, Ningde, Fuzhou, Quanzhou and Putian.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26532" num="14" wdcount="21"> BFN [Text] Comrade Wen Jiabao 
[member of CPC Central Committee Secretariat] and his party left 
Changsha for Zhuzhou and Xiangtan yesterday.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26532" num="16" wdcount="24"> After listening to reports 
submitted by the two cities on their efforts to fight the flooding and 
do relief work, he issued important instructions.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26604" num="5" wdcount="3"> 23 Jun 1994</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26604" num="15" wdcount="28"> BFN [Text] Guangzhou, June 23 
(XINHUA) -- The highest flood peaks on the Xijiang and Beijiang Rivers 
have passed, said Zhu Senlin, governor of south China's Guangdong 
Province.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26604" num="23" wdcount="37"> According to him, 11 million 
people in the province's nine cities and 55 counties were affected, and 
more than 200 people died in the natural disaster, with 189,000 rooms 
destroyed and 1.2 million hectares of crops ruined.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26768" num="5" wdcount="3"> 24 Jun 1994</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26768" num="8" wdcount="7"> Wen Jiabao Inspects Flood 
Situation in Jiangxi</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26768" num="24" wdcount="6"> Jiangxi is a major agricultural 
province.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26768" num="25" wdcount="38"> We should take measures to 
promptly salvage the early-ripening rice, and should expand the 
planting of late-ripening rice and autumn grain as much as possible so 
as to attain a bumper harvest of grain for the whole year.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26769" num="5" wdcount="3"> 26 Jun 1994</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-26769" num="14" wdcount="42"> BFN [Text] Beijing, June 26 
(XINHUA) -- Floods have all receded along Xijiang, Beijiang, Xiangjiang 
and Ganjiang except at a section of the Xijiang River in Wuzhou city, 
Guangxi, a spokesman from the State Flood Control and Drought Relief 
Headquarters announced today.</s>
